>>51614993
Usually, that's when you have it easy.
Then again, I'm actually in the same situation as you on multiple stories. I have the first few scenes and eaith know or have written what should happen at the quarter-mark.
If your outline answers what roughly needs to happen at the half and three-quarters marks as well, then you're well on your way. It does worry me that you've tagged yourself as mystery; without going through the whole 35k I can't be too specific.
But I can advise that if there is a real mystery/thriller/suspense plot in there, hit your notes. The bits you've already set up in previous scenes need to connect to something and should point to the who/what/why/when/where/how.
Maybe it's figuring out the problem/response flow that strings scenes together. Maybe you already know that X guessed something about Y, but not the whole truth, and events spiral off of that.

Then again, I live and die by my notes. Once I get to a scene, I pants the fuck out of it after prompting myself with what the immediate problem or conflict is.
Your milage may vary
